# Creating a Simple Accordion with Radix UI

You can create a simple accordion using Radix UI's `Accordion` component. Here's a step-by-step guide:

## 1. First, install the Accordion component

```bash
npm install @radix-ui/react-accordion
# or
yarn add @radix-ui/react-accordion
```

## 2. Create a basic accordion

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import * as Accordion from '@radix-ui/react-accordion';
import { ChevronDownIcon } from '@radix-ui/react-icons';

const SimpleAccordion = () => {
  return (
    <Accordion.Root
      className="w-full max-w-md" 
      type="single" 
      defaultValue="item-1" 
      collapsible
    >
      <AccordionItem value="item-1">
        <AccordionTrigger>What is Radix UI?</AccordionTrigger>
        <AccordionContent>
          Radix UI is a low-level UI component library with a focus on accessibility, 
          customization and developer experience.
        </AccordionContent>
      </AccordionItem>

      <AccordionItem value="item-2">
        <AccordionTrigger>Is it accessible?</AccordionTrigger>
        <AccordionContent>
          Yes. Radix UI components are built with accessibility in mind, following WAI-ARIA design patterns.
        </AccordionContent>
      </AccordionItem>

      <AccordionItem value="item-3">
        <AccordionTrigger>Can I style it easily?</AccordionTrigger>
        <AccordionContent>
          Absolutely! Radix UI components are unstyled by default, so you can add any styling you want.
        </AccordionContent>
      </AccordionItem>
    </Accordion.Root>
  );
};

// Sub-components for better organization
const AccordionItem = ({ children, value }) => (
  <Accordion.Item 
    value={value}
    className="mt-2 border border-gray-200 rounded-md overflow-hidden"
  >
    {children}
  </Accordion.Item>
);

const AccordionTrigger = ({ children }) => (
  <Accordion.Header>
    <Accordion.Trigger className="flex items-center justify-between w-full px-4 py-3 text-left bg-white hover:bg-gray-50">
      <span>{children}</span>
      <ChevronDownIcon className="w-4 h-4 transition-transform duration-300 ease-in-out accordion-down" aria-hidden />
    </Accordion.Trigger>
  </Accordion.Header>
);

const AccordionContent = ({ children }) => (
  <Accordion.Content className="px-4 py-3 bg-white">
    <div className="text-sm text-gray-700">{children}</div>
  </Accordion.Content>
);

export default SimpleAccordion;
```

## 3. Add some basic styling (CSS)

Add this to your CSS file:

```css
/* For the chevron animation */
.accordion-down {
  transform: rotate(0deg);
}

[data-state="open"] .accordion-down {
  transform: rotate(180deg);
}

/* For animation when opening/closing */
[data-state="open"] {
  animation: slideDown 300ms ease-out;
}

[data-state="closed"] {
  animation: slideUp 300ms ease-out;
}

@keyframes slideDown {
  from {
    height: 0;
  }
  to {
    height: var(--radix-accordion-content-height);
  }
}

@keyframes slideUp {
  from {
    height: var(--radix-accordion-content-height);
  }
  to {
    height: 0;
  }
}
```

## 4. Usage in your application

```jsx
import SimpleAccordion from './SimpleAccordion';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="p-6">
      <h1 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
      <SimpleAccordion />
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Key features of this accordion

- **Accessibility**: Fully accessible, with proper ARIA attributes
- **Keyboard navigation**: Can be navigated with Tab and operated with Enter/Space
- **Animation**: Smooth animation when opening/closing items
- **Customizable**: You can easily change styles or content
- **Stateful**: You can control which item is open via the `defaultValue` prop
- **Types**: "single" (only one item open at a time) or "multiple" (multiple items can be open)

This provides a solid foundation that you can extend with more advanced features or styling as needed!
