# Reusable Empty Accordion Component with Radix UI

Here's a clean, reusable accordion component that's empty by default and can be customized with your own content:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import * as Accordion from '@radix-ui/react-accordion';
import { ChevronDownIcon } from '@radix-ui/react-icons';

/**
 * AccordionItem Component
 * 
 * @param {Object} props
 * @param {string} props.value - Unique identifier for the accordion item
 * @param {React.ReactNode} props.trigger - Content for the trigger button
 * @param {React.ReactNode} props.content - Content to display when expanded
 * @param {string} [props.className] - Additional CSS classes
 */
export const AccordionItem = ({ value, trigger, content, className = '' }) => (
  <Accordion.Item 
    value={value} 
    className={`mt-2 border border-gray-200 rounded-md overflow-hidden ${className}`}
  >
    <Accordion.Header>
      <Accordion.Trigger className="flex items-center justify-between w-full px-4 py-3 text-left bg-white hover:bg-gray-50">
        <span>{trigger}</span>
        <ChevronDownIcon className="w-4 h-4 transition-transform duration-300 ease-in-out accordion-down" aria-hidden />
      </Accordion.Trigger>
    </Accordion.Header>
    <Accordion.Content className="px-4 py-3 bg-white overflow-hidden">
      <div className="text-sm text-gray-700">
        {content}
      </div>
    </Accordion.Content>
  </Accordion.Item>
);

/**
 * SimpleAccordion Component
 * 
 * @param {Object} props
 * @param {React.ReactNode} props.children - AccordionItem components
 * @param {string} [props.type="single"] - "single" or "multiple"
 * @param {string} [props.defaultValue] - The value of the item to open by default
 * @param {boolean} [props.collapsible=true] - If true, allows closing all items
 * @param {string} [props.className] - Additional CSS classes
 */
const SimpleAccordion = ({ 
  children, 
  type = "single", 
  defaultValue, 
  collapsible = true, 
  className = "" 
}) => {
  return (
    <Accordion.Root
      className={`w-full ${className}`}
      type={type}
      defaultValue={defaultValue}
      collapsible={collapsible}
    >
      {children}
    </Accordion.Root>
  );
};

export default SimpleAccordion;
```

## Usage Example

Here's how you would use this reusable component:

```jsx
import SimpleAccordion, { AccordionItem } from './SimpleAccordion';

const FAQSection = () => {
  return (
    <div className="p-6">
      <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <SimpleAccordion defaultValue="item-1">
        <AccordionItem 
          value="item-1"
          trigger="What is Radix UI?"
          content={
            <p>
              Radix UI is a low-level UI component library with a focus on accessibility, 
              customization and developer experience.
            </p>
          }
        />

        <AccordionItem 
          value="item-2"
          trigger="Is it accessible?"
          content={
            <p>
              Yes! Radix UI components follow WAI-ARIA design patterns for 
              maximum accessibility.
            </p>
          }
        />

        <AccordionItem 
          value="item-3"
          trigger="Can I use complex content inside?"
          content={
            <div>
              <p>You can insert any React component or HTML content, like:</p>
              <ul className="list-disc ml-5 mt-2">
                <li>Lists</li>
                <li>Images</li>
                <li>Other components</li>
              </ul>
              <button className="mt-3 px-4 py-2 bg-blue-500 text-white rounded">
                Interactive elements
              </button>
            </div>
          }
        />
      </SimpleAccordion>
    </div>
  );
};
```

## CSS Styles (Add to your stylesheet)

```css
/* For the chevron animation */
.accordion-down {
  transform: rotate(0deg);
}

[data-state="open"] .accordion-down {
  transform: rotate(180deg);
}

/* For animation when opening/closing */
[data-state="open"] [data-radix-accordion-content] {
  animation: slideDown 300ms ease-out;
}

[data-state="closed"] [data-radix-accordion-content] {
  animation: slideUp 300ms ease-out;
}

@keyframes slideDown {
  from {
    height: 0;
  }
  to {
    height: var(--radix-accordion-content-height);
  }
}

@keyframes slideUp {
  from {
    height: var(--radix-accordion-content-height);
  }
  to {
    height: 0;
  }
}
```

## Features

- **Empty & Reusable**: The base component accepts any content
- **Flexible**: Customize trigger and content separately
- **Well-typed**: Includes JSDoc comments for better type hinting
- **Configurable**: Control behavior with props like `type`, `defaultValue`, and `collapsible`
- **Extensible**: Add your own CSS classes with the `className` prop

You can now use this accordion component throughout your application with different content and styling as needed!
Where are radix components installed?

# Where Radix UI Components Are Installed

When you install Radix UI components, they are stored in a few specific locations:

## 1. In Your Project's `node_modules` Directory

After running `npm install` or `yarn add`, Radix UI packages are installed in your project's `node_modules` directory:

```
node_modules/
  ├── @radix-ui/
  │   ├── react-accordion/
  │   ├── react-dialog/
  │   ├── themes/
  │   ├── ... (other Radix components)
  │   └── primitive/ (core functionality)
  └── ... (other dependencies)
```

## 2. Package Structure

Each Radix UI component is published as a separate package under the `@radix-ui` namespace:

- **Primitives**: `@radix-ui/react-*` (e.g., `@radix-ui/react-accordion`)
- **Themes**: `@radix-ui/themes`
- **Icons**: `@radix-ui/react-icons`

## 3. In Your Project's `package.json`

The components you've installed will be listed as dependencies in your project's `package.json` file:

```json
{
  "dependencies": {
    "@radix-ui/react-accordion": "^1.1.2",
    "@radix-ui/themes": "^2.0.0",
    "@radix-ui/react-icons": "^1.3.0",
    // other dependencies
  }
}
```

## 4. Importing Components

When you use Radix UI components in your code, you import them directly from their respective packages:

```jsx
// Importing a Primitive component
import * as Accordion from '@radix-ui/react-accordion';

// Importing from Themes
import { Theme, Button } from '@radix-ui/themes';

// Importing an icon
import { ChevronDownIcon } from '@radix-ui/react-icons';
```

## 5. Finding Component Documentation

To find which components are available:

1. Visit the [Radix UI website](https://www.radix-ui.com/)
2. Explore the Primitives section for individual unstyled components
3. Explore the Themes section for the styled component library

Each component has its own documentation page with installation instructions, examples, and API details.

## Important Note

Radix UI has two main offerings:

1. **Radix Primitives**: Unstyled, accessible components that you style yourself
2. **Radix Themes**: Pre-styled components built on top of Primitives

They are used differently, so make sure you're following the correct documentation for the one you're using.
